Nevermind, I found this pull request. I opened a JIRA to track that: https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SAMZA-941.

@michaelwong95 could you let me know your Apache account? We need that to assign the JIRAs.

Thanks!

@velee Your patch has been committed in SAMZA-767.
Can you close this PR? 

Thanks!

@nickpan47 Unfortunately, I could not find ways to close this from the github UI. (Maybe, I don't have accesses on the github repo provisioned correctly). Also, I believe the mirror is read-only. 

From some misc docs [here](https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/REEF/Accepting+Pull+Requests): 
Further, the mirror on GitHub is read-only. Which means we can neither accept nor close pull requests filled there via the GitHub web UI.

@vjagadish1989 Yeah. I don't have problem creating a task that throws exception. The problem is ensuring that the correct execution path is triggered through my unit test. It can be done only when I bring up a fully operational processor, like I do in TestStreamProcessor. I felt it was a tad-bit unnecessary for adding this test at this point. Thanks for your quick review, btw! 

@xinyuiscool Check [here](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SAMZA-1084?focusedCommentId=15866556&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-15866556) for details. It basically didn't seem like a big value add for the user. I remember this conclusion is different from what we had discussed previously.
> I am not sure whether you plan to add more samza specific stuff to this ProcessorLifecyleCallback interface. 

As of today, we don't intend to include anything else on this callback. 

> If we just need to know when it's complete and failure, you can use java8 CompletableFuture. You can wire up your single thread executor with that easily (something like this: http://www.nurkiewicz.com/2015/11/which-thread-executes.html)

That sounds awesome! I didn't know about this. Let me give it a read and see if it works for us. Thanks!

@jmakes : 

Fixed the broken tests. 

I've added Map(SystemName -> SystemAdmins) in the classes DefaultChooser and BootstrappingChooser. In tests, those values were not set correctly. Hence the failures.

Thank you for the patch!

@logarithm Can we please open a [DISCUSS] thread in the open source mailing list? IMHO, it'd be a good idea to seek comments from more stakeholders. 

In addition to this, it has other ramifications like for example, the name of the binaries that a Samza release publishes to the maven artifactory.

@jmakes 
Please take a look when you get a chance.

The build was successful (https://builds.apache.org/job/samza-pr-checks/111/), however the github-jenkins plugin doesn't update the result here.
